WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.119 --> 00:00:01.119
Hey there!

00:00:01.119 --> 00:00:04.290
I’m Mike Rugnetta, this is Crash Course
Theater, and today we’re looking at two

00:00:04.290 --> 00:00:07.549
very different models of radical, transformative
theater.

00:00:07.549 --> 00:00:10.510
First, we’ll head to Poland for Jerzy Grotowski’s
Poor Theater.

00:00:10.510 --> 00:00:15.549
Then, we’ll zoom over to Brazil for Augusto
Boal’s The Theater of the Oppressed.

00:00:15.549 --> 00:00:20.100
These are pretty different movements: one
is mostly concerned with personal discovery

00:00:20.100 --> 00:00:23.630
and the other is about creating broader social
change.

00:00:23.630 --> 00:00:28.800
But both of them do away with theatrical conventions
like costumes and scenery.

00:00:28.800 --> 00:00:31.570
They are even kind of meh on props.

00:00:31.570 --> 00:00:36.300
Eh, but you’re kinda like more of a “co-star.”

00:00:36.300 --> 00:00:40.420
And both try to break down barriers between
actors and audiences, remaking the theater

00:00:40.420 --> 00:00:44.519
as a space to create real and lasting change.

00:00:44.519 --> 00:00:50.780
Let’s rise up!

00:00:50.780 --> 00:00:57.839
INTRO
Poor Theater was started by this guy, Jerzy

00:00:57.839 --> 00:00:58.839
Grotowski.

00:00:58.839 --> 00:01:04.000
He was born in Poland in 1933 and later educated
in Moscow at the Russian Academy of Theater

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:05.000
Arts.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:09.110
In 1959, he settled in Opole in Poland and
began to work with a group of artists who

00:01:09.110 --> 00:01:11.670
would form the Polish Laboratory Theater.

00:01:11.670 --> 00:01:16.750
In the early 1980s, he left Poland, moving
first to America, where he taught at several

00:01:16.750 --> 00:01:18.830
universities, and then to Italy.

00:01:18.830 --> 00:01:24.530
Like Stanislavski, who was both a big influence
and a big rival , Grotowski was a charismatic

00:01:24.530 --> 00:01:28.260
figure who tried to create a new style of
acting.

00:01:28.260 --> 00:01:33.280
While Stanislavski’s style is based in psychological
realism, Grotowski moved away from realism

00:01:33.280 --> 00:01:36.730
and toward something more ritualistic and
elemental.

00:01:36.730 --> 00:01:39.950
Grotowski’s theater had two main phases.

00:01:39.950 --> 00:01:41.390
Poor Theater was first.

00:01:41.390 --> 00:01:45.780
The other, which he developed after 1970,
is called the Theater of Sources.

00:01:45.780 --> 00:01:50.240
We’ll mostly focus on Poor Theater, because
it was the more influential of the two and

00:01:50.240 --> 00:01:55.890
because Grotowski compiled a very handy book
about it, “Towards a Poor Theater,” published

00:01:55.890 --> 00:01:59.090
in 1968, that was widely influential.

00:01:59.090 --> 00:02:03.100
If you have any interest in avant-garde theater,
it’s definitely worth a read.

00:02:03.100 --> 00:02:05.020
What is a poor theater?

00:02:05.020 --> 00:02:08.310
Well—surprise!—it’s the opposite of
a rich theater.

00:02:08.310 --> 00:02:10.719
A rich theater doesn’t have to be all that
rich.

00:02:10.719 --> 00:02:16.930
It includes everything from glitzy multimillion-dollar
Broadway productions to amateur shows in church

00:02:16.930 --> 00:02:17.930
basements.

00:02:17.930 --> 00:02:24.030
What all rich theater has in common, though,
is lights and make-up and costumes and sets.

00:02:24.030 --> 00:02:26.939
It is deliberately illusionistic.

00:02:26.939 --> 00:02:29.409
The poor theater has none of that!

00:02:29.409 --> 00:02:31.310
Not a single rotating gobo.

00:02:31.310 --> 00:02:36.609
Instead, it relies on the power of the actor
to convey character and setting.

00:02:36.609 --> 00:02:41.290
Grotowski writes:
“One must ask oneself what is indispensable

00:02:41.290 --> 00:02:42.290
to theatre.

00:02:42.290 --> 00:02:43.290
Let’s see.

00:02:43.290 --> 00:02:46.069
“Can the theatre exist without costumes
and sets?

00:02:46.069 --> 00:02:47.359
Yes, it can.

00:02:47.359 --> 00:02:51.030
“Can it exist without music to accompany
the plot?

00:02:51.030 --> 00:02:52.030
Yes.

00:02:52.030 --> 00:02:55.120
“Can it exist without lighting effects?

00:02:55.120 --> 00:02:56.120
Of course.

00:02:56.120 --> 00:02:58.279
“And without a text?

00:02:58.279 --> 00:02:59.279
Yes.”

00:02:59.279 --> 00:03:01.410
Why exist without all this stuff?

00:03:01.410 --> 00:03:02.670
A couple of reasons.

00:03:02.670 --> 00:03:07.700
One of them is that Grotowski realized that
theater was in competition with film and television.

00:03:07.700 --> 00:03:12.159
And if illusionism was what you were after,
then film and television were going to do

00:03:12.159 --> 00:03:15.040
a way, way better job delivering it.

00:03:15.040 --> 00:03:20.430
But what film and television can’t do, Grotowski
reasoned, is to tap back into theater’s

00:03:20.430 --> 00:03:22.749
origins in ritual and myth.

00:03:22.749 --> 00:03:26.790
Maybe you’re thinking, hey, that sounds
like Artaud.

00:03:26.790 --> 00:03:31.260
And you’re not wrong, although, as you maybe
remember from our earlier episode, Artaud

00:03:31.260 --> 00:03:34.599
had no problem with big splashy effects.

00:03:34.599 --> 00:03:35.599
Aaah!

00:03:35.599 --> 00:03:38.590
So many frogs, scorpions and jets of blood!

00:03:38.590 --> 00:03:42.969
Another reason for poor theater is that Grotowski
wanted to eliminate the separation between

00:03:42.969 --> 00:03:45.209
the actors and the audience.

00:03:45.209 --> 00:03:51.260
If spectators don’t get to have fancy wigs
and spotlights, then neither should the actors!

00:03:51.260 --> 00:03:55.719
In most of Grotowski’s productions, the
audience mingled with the actors or surrounded

00:03:55.719 --> 00:04:00.290
the actors on all sides, so that they everyone
occupied the playing space.

00:04:00.290 --> 00:04:04.230
The performers were constantly exposed and
unmiked.

00:04:04.230 --> 00:04:10.099
Grotowski and his actors would spend years
rehearsing productions, refining every movement,

00:04:10.099 --> 00:04:12.489
every breath, every facial expression.

00:04:12.489 --> 00:04:19.069
And yet actors still described a feeling of
intense spontaneity and emotional connection

00:04:19.069 --> 00:04:20.069
to the work.

00:04:20.069 --> 00:04:25.550
Maja Komorowska, an actor in the company,
said it was a “precise, meticulous composition,

00:04:25.550 --> 00:04:29.669
but there wasn't the slightest sign of artificiality…

00:04:29.669 --> 00:04:36.030
This explosion, an eruption of emotion and
truth—[it] was no longer merely theater."

00:04:36.030 --> 00:04:39.280
Grotowski believed that a role should “penetrate”
the actor.

00:04:39.280 --> 00:04:42.860
That’s his word—well, except he said it
in Polish.

00:04:42.860 --> 00:04:47.150
Grotowski’s method required that an actor
open themselves to the role completely.

00:04:47.150 --> 00:04:52.660
Ryszard Cieślak, for many years his lead
actor, said of Grotowski’s style, “It

00:04:52.660 --> 00:04:57.870
is anyhow impossible to treat it in merely
artistic terms.

00:04:57.870 --> 00:05:03.430
It resulted in my fundamental transformation,
not only as an actor, but also as a human

00:05:03.430 --> 00:05:04.430
being.”

00:05:04.430 --> 00:05:06.090
You might say this all sounds kinda… religious.

00:05:06.090 --> 00:05:08.479
And you’re not wrong.

00:05:08.479 --> 00:05:12.400
Director Peter Brook, who observed Grotowski
at work, considered Grotowski an example of

00:05:12.400 --> 00:05:15.210
holy or sacred theater.

00:05:15.210 --> 00:05:20.729
Brook called this style of acting, an “act
of sacrifice, of sacrificing what most men

00:05:20.729 --> 00:05:25.669
prefer to hide—this sacrifice is his gift
to the spectator.”

00:05:25.669 --> 00:05:29.580
Brook wrote that in Grotowski’s poor theater,
actors give up everything except for the power

00:05:29.580 --> 00:05:35.920
of their own bodies and unlimited rehearsal
time to bring those bodies to the role: “No

00:05:35.920 --> 00:05:40.010
wonder they feel the richest theatre in the
world.”

00:05:40.010 --> 00:05:41.550
… GET IT?

00:05:41.550 --> 00:05:42.550
Richest Theater?

00:05:42.550 --> 00:05:45.060
For a closer look at Grotowski’s methods
and style, let’s explore one of his most

00:05:45.060 --> 00:05:50.220
famous and —fair warning—most disturbing
works, “Akropolis.”

00:05:50.220 --> 00:05:56.849
“Akropolis,” first performed in 1962,
was based on a long 1904 poetic drama by Stanisław

00:05:56.849 --> 00:05:57.849
Wyspianski.

00:05:57.849 --> 00:06:03.160
A shout-out to Western culture and a call
for Polish national pride, it describes how

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:07.930
statues, tapestries, and carvings come to
life in a Krakow cathedral on the night before

00:06:07.930 --> 00:06:08.930
Easter.

00:06:08.930 --> 00:06:13.240
But Grotowski transferred the setting to Auschwitz,
not all that far away from his theater in

00:06:13.240 --> 00:06:19.040
Opole, and created a piece asking if culture
could matter at all after an event like the

00:06:19.040 --> 00:06:20.040
Holocaust.

