00:06:24.040 --> 00:06:25.040
The audience is seated on all four sides of
the space.

00:06:25.040 --> 00:06:27.650
In the middle is a junk heap—pipes, nails,
a rusting bathtub.

00:06:27.650 --> 00:06:30.699
Above the heap is a web of ropes, a little
like barbed wire.

00:06:30.699 --> 00:06:32.370
This is a concentration camp.

00:06:32.370 --> 00:06:36.919
At the beginning of the play, an actor drags
in a headless dummy and delivers a prologue.

00:06:36.919 --> 00:06:41.810
Then the other actors, dressed identically
in tunics, berets, and heavy wooden-soled

00:06:41.810 --> 00:06:43.500
shoes, enter.

00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:45.840
Their faces are frozen into grimaces.

00:06:45.840 --> 00:06:49.569
Grotowski called these facial expressions
“life masks.”

00:06:49.569 --> 00:06:52.370
One observer wrote that their eyes actually
look dead.

00:06:52.370 --> 00:06:55.560
They speak like a Greek chorus:
CHORUS:

00:06:55.560 --> 00:06:58.340
Only once a year,
They come only once a year

00:06:58.340 --> 00:07:00.370
On the cemetery of the tribes.

00:07:00.370 --> 00:07:02.180
A SINGLE VOICE:
Our Acropolis.

00:07:02.180 --> 00:07:04.370
CHORUS:
They read the words of judgment

00:07:04.370 --> 00:07:06.620
On the cemetery of the tribes.

00:07:06.620 --> 00:07:09.169
They're gone and the smoke lingers on.

00:07:09.169 --> 00:07:13.699
Two actors become angels, and they suspend
the headless dummy from the ropes in a pose

00:07:13.699 --> 00:07:14.979
like the crucified Christ.

00:07:14.979 --> 00:07:19.630
A violin plays, and several of the actors
begin to work with materials from the junk

00:07:19.630 --> 00:07:20.630
heap.

00:07:20.630 --> 00:07:24.090
They are building the crematorium where the
prisoners will be burnt.

00:07:24.090 --> 00:07:25.639
Three of the actors step out.

00:07:25.639 --> 00:07:30.409
Two become guards, and the third is a prisoner
whom they interrogate and torture.

00:07:30.409 --> 00:07:35.500
There is more work on the junk pile, an unhappy
sex scene between a man and a woman, and then

00:07:35.500 --> 00:07:38.139
the retelling of the biblical story of Jacob.

00:07:38.139 --> 00:07:41.379
The crematorium is completed; the action shifts
to Troy.

00:07:41.379 --> 00:07:44.630
There is a scene between Paris and Helen.

00:07:44.630 --> 00:07:49.610
One prisoner steps out to become King David,
and he addresses a speech to God that ends

00:07:49.610 --> 00:07:50.919
in a wild song.

00:07:50.919 --> 00:07:55.690
And the dummy is lifted overhead, an image
of a dead, starved prisoner.

00:07:55.690 --> 00:07:59.840
One by one, the actors throw themselves into
a pit.

00:07:59.840 --> 00:08:00.840
Thanks, ThoughtBubble.

00:08:00.840 --> 00:08:05.759
That whole thing took fifty minutes, and at
the end, the audience was usually too upset

00:08:05.759 --> 00:08:06.759
to applaud..

00:08:06.759 --> 00:08:10.800
By 1970, Grotowski figured he’d gone about
as far as he could go in perfecting the work

00:08:10.800 --> 00:08:11.800
of the actor.

00:08:11.800 --> 00:08:17.900
So he turned to eliminating the divide between
actor and audience, creating “a meeting,

00:08:17.900 --> 00:08:22.650
not a confrontation; a communion where we
can be totally ourselves.”

00:08:22.650 --> 00:08:28.219
He also undertook an extensive study of ritual
performance in Asia, Africa and the Caribbean:

00:08:28.219 --> 00:08:30.080
the Theater of Sources.

00:08:30.080 --> 00:08:31.090
He died in 1999.

00:08:31.090 --> 00:08:35.740
Let’s turn to another theatermaker interested
in blurring boundaries between actor and audience.

00:08:35.740 --> 00:08:40.250
That would be this guy, Augusto Boal, born
in Brazil in 1931.

00:08:40.250 --> 00:08:44.830
Initially he studied chemical engineering,
but while he was a student at Columbia University,

00:08:44.830 --> 00:08:48.300
he was introduced to the theories of Brecht
and Stanislavski.

00:08:48.300 --> 00:08:53.519
Later on, he was also profoundly influenced
by the educator Paolo Freire, who pioneered

00:08:53.519 --> 00:08:58.260
the “Pedagogy of the Oppressed,” a nonhierarchical
educational method.

00:08:58.260 --> 00:09:02.450
Returning to Brazil, Boal began to direct
plays at the Arena Theater.

00:09:02.450 --> 00:09:05.769
First classics and then plays written by Brazilian
playwrights.

00:09:05.769 --> 00:09:08.420
He toured his plays to poor neighborhoods.

00:09:08.420 --> 00:09:13.600
These plays often ended with actors asking
their audience to rise above oppression.

00:09:13.600 --> 00:09:18.760
But Boal began to think that, instead of just
talking to audiences, he should be listening

00:09:18.760 --> 00:09:21.730
to them and empowering them.

00:09:21.730 --> 00:09:26.420
As his practices evolved, he encouraged audiences
to talk back to the action—you can see the

00:09:26.420 --> 00:09:30.829
influence of Brecht here—and to suggest
new actions for the characters.

00:09:30.829 --> 00:09:34.750
Legend has it that, during one performance,
a female audience member couldn’t make an

00:09:34.750 --> 00:09:36.959
actor understand her suggestion.

00:09:36.959 --> 00:09:40.690
So she stepped onstage and performed the action
herself.

00:09:40.690 --> 00:09:43.450
This birthed the idea of the spect-actor.

00:09:43.450 --> 00:09:45.100
[[[Yorick flies in wearing spectacles.]]]

00:09:45.100 --> 00:09:46.100
No, no, no.

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:51.560
The spect-actor is part spectator and part
actor and all awesome.

00:09:51.560 --> 00:09:52.560
Unlike those glasses.

00:09:52.560 --> 00:09:54.680
Get out of here.

00:09:54.680 --> 00:09:57.011
This method eventually became known as Forum
Theater.

00:09:57.011 --> 00:10:02.420
A Forum Theater exercise begins with a short
scene centered on a social problem—sexism,

00:10:02.420 --> 00:10:05.360
say, or racial discrimination.

00:10:05.360 --> 00:10:07.670
After the scene concludes, it starts again.

00:10:07.670 --> 00:10:14.470
And this time, spect-actors are invited to
interrupt the proceeding with their own actions.

00:10:14.470 --> 00:10:18.500
A facilitator, usually called a “joker,”
monitors the performance.

00:10:18.500 --> 00:10:20.760
The “joker” doesn’t actually joke.

00:10:20.760 --> 00:10:25.720
They make sure that each spect-actor is able
to complete his or her action, and then asks

00:10:25.720 --> 00:10:31.649
the audience to evaluate the usefulness of
each proposed solution to the social problem.

00:10:31.649 --> 00:10:33.949
If you are freaked out by participatory theater—if
your idea of theater is hiding in the dark

00:10:33.949 --> 00:10:38.630
and ruffling your Playbill, perhaps at most
glaring carefully at someone unwrapping a

00:10:38.630 --> 00:10:42.700
bit of candy in the dark—Theater of the
Oppressed is not for you!

00:10:42.700 --> 00:10:48.370
Boal believed that encouraging audience members
to step onstage was a way of empowering them.

00:10:48.370 --> 00:10:52.760
This meant showing them that they could take
action in their own lives if they felt that

00:10:52.760 --> 00:10:54.440
they were experiencing injustice.

00:10:54.440 --> 00:10:57.899
This didn’t sit too well with Brazil’s
military regime.

00:10:57.899 --> 00:11:03.540
And in 1971, after a performance of Brecht’s
“Resistible Rise of Arturo Ui,” Boal was

00:11:03.540 --> 00:11:06.320
kidnapped, tortured, and eventually exiled.

00:11:06.320 --> 00:11:11.269
Boal took his participatory show on the road,
eventually settling in Paris and continuing

00:11:11.269 --> 00:11:12.810
to teach.

00:11:12.810 --> 00:11:16.199
In 1979, he published his first book “Theater
of the Oppressed.”

00:11:16.199 --> 00:11:20.470
He also pioneered another form of political
theater, “Invisible Theater,” which is

00:11:20.470 --> 00:11:23.470
a kind of theater that the audience doesn’t
even know is theater.

00:11:23.470 --> 00:11:27.850
It could be happening anywhere, anytime—it
could be right behind you right now!

00:11:27.850 --> 00:11:29.290
But probably not.

00:11:29.290 --> 00:11:34.880
He re-relocated to Brazil in 1986, became
a city councilman, and pioneered a form known

00:11:34.880 --> 00:11:36.880
as Legislative Theater.

00:11:36.880 --> 00:11:41.570
In this form, citizens were encouraged to
participate in scenes that helped to identify

00:11:41.570 --> 00:11:46.240
the social problems they were facing and to
brainstorm possible solutions.

00:11:46.240 --> 00:11:48.519
Augusto Boal died in 2009.

00:11:48.519 --> 00:11:51.920
Obviously, Grotowski and Boal were pretty
different dudes.

00:11:51.920 --> 00:11:55.200
Grotowski expected actors to rehearse for
years.

00:11:55.200 --> 00:11:58.730
Boal didn’t need his spect-actors to rehearse
at all.

00:11:58.730 --> 00:12:03.070
But both believed in theater as a means to
achieve something greater.

00:12:03.070 --> 00:12:08.709
For Grotowski, that’s a profound self-knowledge
and exploration of the human condition.

00:12:08.709 --> 00:12:15.079
For Boal, that’s the hope of true social
justice and solutions to endemic problems

00:12:15.079 --> 00:12:16.920
discovered as a community.

00:12:16.920 --> 00:12:17.920
CONCLUSION
Thanks for watching.

00:12:17.920 --> 00:12:22.880
Next time, we’ll make our first visit to
West Africa, studying intersections of theater

00:12:22.880 --> 00:12:27.709
and ritual, and exploring Nigeria’s influential
postcolonial theater with a closer look at

00:12:27.709 --> 00:12:29.540
playwright Wole Soyinka.

00:12:29.540 --> 00:13:04.910
Until then… curtain!

